Motivation¶

Thoreau once said, I make myself rich by making my wants few. What if you could make yourself rich even when you have many wants?

The trick is - pick the right career!

Picking a career is often one of the toughest decisions we make. You often wonder Am I in the right career? How much does each career generally make? Which work class is the best? Is my education level good enough? Should I keep studying?

And we are here to answer all your questions! Money is one of the main motivations people have for job. In this tutorial, we analyzed a financial dataset of adults pertaining to incomes from the UCI (University of California, Irvine) database. The dataset originally belonged to the US Census Bureau, therefore, contains accurate information about working adults. The dataset contains data of 48,842 working adults, including details like age, work class, education, marital status, occupation, relationship, race, sex, native country, and work hours per week. Our goal is to predict whether a working adult makes more than $50K per year judging from all the descriptions listed above using machine learning.

Imports¶

We're going to be using the python modules numpy and pandas for our base data storage and handling. numpy provides array and strictly sized integer and floating point types for python, and is also a requirement for pandas. pandas provides the Dataframe structure for data manipulation and analysis.

To plot data for exploratory analysis, we will use pyplot and folium. pyplot can draw plots of numerical data. folium is a python module used for generating interactive maps and plotting data to them.

To test our hypotheses about the data, we will use scipy. scipy contains a myriad of useful scientific functions, but we will be using it specifically for its statistical capabilities.

Lastly, for machine learning we will be using many of the subpackages of scikit-learn, abbreviated sklearn in the module name.

The module warnings is merely used to hide deprecation warnings from older functions. While ordinarily something to worry about, these will vanish as modules dependent on numpy are updated.

Data Loading¶

Now that we've imported the libraries we need, we can load our data. We're going to be using a table of census data from the UCI Machine Learning Repository. You can dowload this dataset from https://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml/datasets/adult. The contents contain both the training data as 'Dataset.data' and the specifications as 'Dataset.spec'.
We can then start by importing this data into a pandas dataframe.
Looking at the data file, we can see that the data is separated by spaces. Also, there does not appear to be any header showing the names of columns, so we're going to have to add those in ourselves. Finally, we can see that on line 5 there is a '?' for the 'workclass' column. This likely indicates a NaN, given that the specifications say that possible values for workclass are all words.
We can account for all this by using some of the numerous options of pandas read_csv function:

  • sep=' ' - sets the separator to spaces instead of commas
  • names=cols - sets the column names to those given in cols
  • na_values='?' - the parser will read all '?'s as NaNs

Data Imputation¶

It looks good! But we still have those '?'s, now converted to NaNs, randomly scattered through the missing data. To deal with them, we'll impute the data. This means that we'll find a way to replace the NaNs with actual values. There are many ways to do this, but we'll be using hot-deck imputation.

Hot-deck imputation is where entries with missing values have these missing values replaced with non-missing values from other entires which are very similar to the entry with the missing value. For example, if A has a missing value and B has no missing values and is similar to A, a value cooresponding from B will be coped to A to replace A's the missing value.

To perform hot-deck imputation, we first have to determine which entries are similar to each other. One quick way to do this is to sort the data, since this will place entries with similar non-missing values close to eachother.

Afterwards, if we want to fill in the missing values of any entry, we can simply look to the entries to the top and bottom of our entry since those will be the most similar to it. This essentially allows us to fill in missing data with that values that the data most likely would have been if it had not been missing.

First we sort the data by all of the columns to place similar rows near each other. However, we have to be a bit careful here. By default, pandas' sort method will place all of the NaN values at the start of the dataframe or at the end of the dataframe. This is not the behavior we want, since this will not place similar rows near each other. Instead, we want the sort to "ignore" the rows containing NaN values and leave them where they are, while the rows around these rows are actually sorted. This has the desired effect of moving similar rows near each other without discriminating against the rows containing NaN values.

To perform this sort, we do the following.

  1. For each column, do the following:
    1. Remove all of the rows containing NaN values in this column
    2. Sort the dataframe based on the entries of this column
    3. Restore the deleted rows in their original positions
  2. Repeat the above procedure for all remaining columns

Here is the sorting algorithm:

In [5]:
df = data.copy()
columns = list(df)

# perform a sort on each column
for c in range(len(df.columns)):
    
    # store the row indices
    indices = []
    
    # find indices of rows containing null values in selected column
    for i, row in df.iterrows():
        if row[c] != row[c]:
            indices.append(i)
    
    # make a copy of the data frame
    df_copy = df.copy()
    
    # remove the rows containing null values in selected column
    df = df.drop(df.index[indices])
    
    # sort the data which no longer contains null values
    df_sorted = df.sort_values(list(df)[c])
    
    # obtain a matrix representation of the dataframe
    mat = df_sorted.values
    
    # insert the deleted rows back into their original positions
    for index in indices:
        
        line_array = df_copy.iloc[index].values        
        mat = np.insert(mat, index, line_array, 0)

    # convert the matrix back into a dataframe
    df = pd.DataFrame(data=mat, columns=columns)
    
data_sorted = df.copy()

In [7]:

Finally we will impute the missing data. For each row with missing data, we will replace with existing data from the closest row above or below. We will do this for all rows containing missing data.

In [8]:
# keep track of the current row
row_index = 0

# get the dataframe length
data_sorted_size = data_sorted.shape[0]

# loop through dataframe data_sorted
for i, row in data_sorted.iterrows():
    
    # determine if current row contains missing data
    if i in data_null_indices:
        
        # go through each field of row containing missing data
        for j in range(len(row)):
            
            # set the upper and lower indices
            above_index = row_index
            below_index = row_index
            
            # flags for whether we sent above or below last time
            went_above = True
            went_below = True
            
            # get the value at the current index
            value = data_sorted.iloc[row_index, j]
            
            # while the value is NaN
            while value != value:
                
                # in the case that we can't go above anymore (go below)
                if above_index <= 0:
                    if below_index < data_sorted_size - 1:
                        below_index = below_index + 1
                        value = data_sorted.iloc[below_index, j]
                
                # in the case that we can't go below anymore (go above)
                elif below_index >= data_sorted_size:
                    if above_index > 0:
                        above_index = above_index - 1
                        value = data_sorted.iloc[above_index, j]
                        
                # if the case that we went below last time (go below)
                elif went_below:
                    above_index = above_index - 1
                    value = data_sorted.iloc[above_index, j]
                    went_above = True
                    went_below = False
                    
                # in the case that we went above last time (go below)
                elif went_above:
                    below_index = below_index + 1
                    value = data_sorted.iloc[below_index, j]
                    went_above = False
                    went_below = True
                    
            
            # make the substitution of the NaN with potentially non-NaN data
            data_sorted.iloc[row_index, j] = value

    # increment the count of the current row
    row_index += 1

data = data_sorted

Now there are no more missing values in the data!

To start with, we want to convert our output variable, expected salary, to a plottable integer. Currently, it's in a textual form representing binary data, and we want it to be integers. To fix this, we can use the DataFrame function map to convert each string to the integer value either 0 or 1.

To examine this data, we want to plot each of the variables with respect to the variable of interest (their salary relative to $50k). We want a nice data structure to allow easy summations along any variable we want, so that we can access any subset of data we need. One such structure is a 5-dimensional array -- one dimension for each feature, and a value for each category. To create this array we simply initialize the structure with all zeros, then iterate over all the data and increment the appropriate intersectional counter for each row.

In [12]:
genders = ['Male', 'Female']
num_genders = len(genders)
races = ['White', 'Asian-Pac-Islander', 'Amer-Indian-Eskimo', 'Other', 'Black']
num_races = len(races)
employments = ['Private', 'Self-emp-not-inc', 'Self-emp-inc', 'Federal-gov',
              'Local-gov', 'State-gov', 'Without-pay', 'Never-worked']
num_employments = len(employments)
marital_statuses = ['Married-civ-spouse', 'Divorced', 'Never-married',
                    'Separated', 'Widowed', 'Married-spouse-absent',
                    'Married-AF-spouse']
num_marital = len(marital_statuses)
occupations = ['Tech-support', 'Craft-repair', 'Other-service', 'Sales',
              'Exec-managerial', 'Prof-specialty', 'Handlers-cleaners',
              'Machine-op-inspct', 'Adm-clerical', 'Farming-fishing',
              'Transport-moving', 'Priv-house-serv', 'Protective-serv',
              'Armed-Forces']
num_occupations = len(occupations)

# gender, race, employment, marital-status, income
low_income_counts = np.zeros((num_genders,num_races,num_employments,num_marital,num_occupations), dtype=np.int32)
high_income_counts = np.zeros((num_genders,num_races,num_employments,num_marital,num_occupations), dtype=np.int32)

for i, row in data.iterrows():
    g = genders.index(row['gender'])
    r = races.index(row['race'])
    e = employments.index(row['workclass'])
    m = marital_statuses.index(row['marital-status'])
    o = occupations.index(row['occupation'])
    i = row['income']
    if i == '<=50K':
        low_income_counts[g,r,e,m,o] += 1
    elif i == '>50K':
        high_income_counts[g,r,e,m,o] += 1

Plot 1 - Percent of Men and Women with High Income¶

To create a plot, we call plt.figure. We find the number of men and women who make more than \$50k/yr respectively, from the 5-dimensional array we created, we set a specific gender and ignore all the other options like races and occupations. We then find the actual percentage and plot it.

Looking at the plot, it seems like in general, of the 45% people who do make more than 50k/yr, 30% of which are male and only around 10% are female.

In [13]:

pos = np.arange(len(genders))
# Low income men, High income men, Low income women, High income women
num = np.sum(high_income_counts, axis=(1,2,3,4))
num = np.divide(num, num + np.sum(low_income_counts, axis=(1,2,3,4)))
plt.bar(pos, num, align='center')
plt.xticks(pos, genders)
plt.xlabel('Gender')
plt.ylabel('Percentage')
plt.title('Percent of Men and Women with High Income')

plt.show()

Plotting maps¶

To make plots by location, we need to do a little more formatting work.

Country Abbreviations¶

In world-countries.json, countries are recognized by its country abbreviation. The following block reads from the json file and uses a regular expression to put a country name as a key and its abbreviation as a value in a dictionary, name_ids.

In [19]:
file = open('world-countries.json')
world_countries = json.load(file)
file.close()

features = world_countries['features']
name_ids = {country['properties']['name']:country['id'] for country in features}

Data Cleaning¶

The following block of code changes the entries in our dataset in order to provide accurate mappings.

Looking at the countries provided in the data, there are several errors, including spelling mistakes and insufficient data. For an example, "Hong", is missing the word "Kong". Sine Folium doesn't have the geotag for Hong Kong, we will put Hong Kong in China. England and Scotland are in United Kingdom, while Holland is mispelled and is in Netherlands. Moreover, Colombia is mispelled as "Columbia". According to the geo json file that folium has, United States' name is "United States of America". Furthermore, the "&'s" in the file is spelled out as "and". Last but not least, "Trinidad" is mispelled as "Trinadad".

In [20]:
data['native-country'] = data['native-country'].map(lambda x: x.replace("-"," "))
data['native-country'] = data['native-country'].map(lambda x: x.replace("Hong","China"))
data['native-country'] = data['native-country'].map(lambda x: 
                                                    x.replace("England","United Kingdom"))
data['native-country'] = data['native-country'].map(lambda x: 
                                                    x.replace("Scotland","United Kingdom"))
data['native-country'] = data['native-country'].map(lambda x: x.replace("Holand ",""))
data['native-country'] = data['native-country'].map(lambda x: x.replace("Columbia","Colombia"))
data['native-country'] = data['native-country'].map(lambda x: 
                                                    x.replace("United States","United States of America"))
data['native-country'] = data['native-country'].map(lambda x: x.replace("&"," and "))
data['native-country'] = data['native-country'].map(lambda x: x.replace("Trinadad","Trinidad"))

Finding Total¶

As the dataset contains data from people of different countries, we would like to find the ratio of people who make more than \$50k per year from each country. In order to do so, we first need to find the total number of people from each country.

The list of unknowns are countries that cannot be mapped as the folium json file does not contain information about their countries.

The total_country dictionary contains the number of people from each country that are in this dataset.

By iterating the dataset, we can then find the country that each person is from, then find the country abbreviation from the name_ids dictionary we made earlier. For each entry add 1 to the appropriate country in order to get the total.

In [21]:
unknown = []
total_country = {}
for index, row in data.iterrows():
    if row["native-country"] in name_ids.keys():
        if name_ids[row["native-country"]] in total_country.keys():
            total_country[name_ids[row["native-country"]]] += 1
        else:
            total_country[name_ids[row["native-country"]]] = 1
    else:
        unknown.append(row["native-country"])

Finding Ratio¶

After finding the total number of entries from each country, we have to find the number of people from each country that makes less than \$50k per year. In order to do that, we create a dictionary, low_income. From a column we generated before (low income, column number 15), containing the binary representation of whether a person makes low income, with 1 being true and 0 as false. So if a person makes less than 50k, the column shows a 1, 0 otherwise.

By going through our data, we can find the entry and add it to its respective country in order to find how many people in a certain country makes less than 50k per year.

In [23]:
low_income = {}
for index,row in data.iterrows():
    if row["native-country"] in name_ids.keys():
        if name_ids[row["native-country"]] in low_income.keys():
            low_income[name_ids[row["native-country"]]] += row["num_income"]
        else:
            low_income[name_ids[row["native-country"]]] = row["num_income"]

Subtracting the total number of people who make less than 50k per year from the total number of people from each country will get us the total number of people that makes more than 50k per year, and dividing it by total multiplying by 100 will get us the percentage, and put that into a dictionary which we called ratio.

Now put ratio as a panda dataframe, with columns "country" and "ratio". Print the head (first five items) to see how it looks like!

In [24]:
ratio = {k:(total_country[k]-low_income[k])/total_country[k]*100 for k in low_income.keys()}
s = pd.DataFrame(list(ratio.items()),columns=['country', 'ratio'])
s.head()

Map1 - Percent of Adults Making Less than 50k/yr by Country¶

Now let's put our information and visualize it on a map!

First, set up a folium map by calling folium.Map(). The world geo tags are from a file called "world-countries.json" from folium, https://github.com/python-visualization/folium/blob/master/examples/data/world-countries.json.

Then, using the pandas dataframe, s, that we obtained from our dictionary ratio, use it as a parameter to plot a choropleth map. We chose the option "YlGn" (yellow and green) as it's easier to read.

The darker the country is, the more people making \$50k/yr.

In [25]:

Average Education Level by Country¶

As we already have the total number of entries from each country, all we need is the total sum of rank of education levels by country (column 4, under "educational-num). In order to get the number, we have to iterate through the dataset, and find the educational num column to obtain its rank. Then add the rank to its respective country like we did before.

In [26]:
education_overall = {}
for index,row in data.iterrows():
    if row["native-country"] in name_ids.keys():
        if name_ids[row["native-country"]] in education_overall.keys():
            education_overall[name_ids[row["native-country"]]] += row["educational-num"]
        else:
            education_overall[name_ids[row["native-country"]]] = row["educational-num"]

By dividing the total overal education by the total number of entry will get an average education level for the people from each country as a whole. Put that number in a dictionary called edu_percent.

Now put edu_percent as a pandas dataframe, let's call it s_edu, with columns "country" and "education". Print the head (first five items) to see how it looks like!

In [27]:
edu_percent = {k:education_overall[k]/total_country[k] for k in total_country.keys()}
s_edu = pd.DataFrame(list(edu_percent.items()),columns=['country', 'education'])

Hypothesis Testing¶

We've seen from the previous plots that expected salary may depend more on some of the variables listed in the Census data than it does on others. In fact, we can see from all the numerical plots that a few categories hold much higher percentages of high salaries than the others. Even from the maps, we can see that some regions tend to have significantly higher salary percentages than the rest. From plot <a href = '#Percent of Men and Women with High Income'>1</a>, for example, it seems that race may have an especially strong effect on salary. Therefore we hypothesize that the mean salary of Asians is higher than that of other races.

First we need to generate a list of the other races to compare Asians against.

In [29]:
comparable_races = list(races)
comparable_races.remove('Asian-Pac-Islander')

Using a Student's t-test, from scipy, we can calculate the probability that the mean salary of Asians is similar to that of each of the other races.

In [30]:
print('Probability that mean salaries are equal to the mean salaries of Asians.')
asian_sample = data[data['race'] == 'Asian-Pac-Islander']['num_income']
for race in comparable_races:
    other_sample = data[data['race'] == race]['num_income']
    (t,p) = scipy.stats.ttest_ind(asian_sample, other_sample, equal_var=False)
    print('{}: {}'.format(race, p))
all_others = data[data['race'] != 'Asian-Pac-Islander']['num_income']
(t,p) = scipy.stats.ttest_ind(asian_sample, all_others, equal_var=False)
print('All non-Asians: {}'.format(p))

Probability that mean salaries are equal to the mean salaries of Asians.
White: 0.18758718893442164
Amer-Indian-Eskimo: 1.1081975038508744e-15
Other: 5.049470571194924e-13
Black: 2.8864232055367824e-32
All non-Asians: 0.007482024869307618

We can extend this statistical test to find the probability that the mean salary of Asians is greater than that of each of the other races.

In [31]:
print('Probability that mean salaries are less than the mean salaries of Asians.')
asian_sample = data[data['race'] == 'Asian-Pac-Islander']['num_income']
for race in comparable_races:
    other_sample = data[data['race'] == race]['num_income']
    (t,p) = scipy.stats.ttest_ind(asian_sample, other_sample, equal_var=False)
    p = 1 - p / 2
    print('{}: {}'.format(race, p))
all_others = data[data['race'] != 'Asian-Pac-Islander']['num_income']
(t,p) = scipy.stats.ttest_ind(asian_sample, all_others, equal_var=False)
p = 1 - p / 2
print('All non-Asians: {}'.format(p))

Probability that mean salaries are less than the mean salaries of Asians.
White: 0.9062064055327892
Amer-Indian-Eskimo: 0.9999999999999994
Other: 0.9999999999997475
Black: 1.0
All non-Asians: 0.9962589875653461

Based on these tests, we can see that with = 0.01, the percentage of Asians with salaries greater than \$50k is higher than that of all other races combined, and higher than that of each individual race except for White.

Machine Learning¶

From the Hypothesis Testing, we've seen that variables like race and gender can have a significant impact on salary. These 'features' can be used to predict a person's salary. To do this, we use the python module sklearn to train machine learning models on a subset of the data, and then test its accuracy on the rest.

To train models on our data we must first encode it appropriately. sklearn does not accept categorical variables, which have a few classes, but will only take numerical data. To make it accept our data we need to first use the pandas.get_dummies function on our categorical columns to convert them to numerical data. The function encodes each possible category of the data as a separate feature, so that rows which were in a specific category instead have a 1 for the feature representing that category and a 0 for features representing the other categories.

In [32]:
categorical_cols = ['workclass', 'marital-status', 'occupation',
                    'relationship', 'race', 'gender', 'native-country']
input_columns = ['age', 'workclass', 'educational-num', 'marital-status',
                 'occupation', 'relationship', 'race', 'gender', 'native-country']
output_column = 'num_income'

onehot_enc = pd.get_dummies(data[input_columns], columns=categorical_cols)
X = onehot_enc.as_matrix()
y = data[output_column].as_matrix()

We also want to split up our data into a training and testing set, so that we can accurately test how well our model predicts the data after training without letting it 'cheat' by seeing the testing data. We do this with the sklearn.model_selection.train_test_split function.

In [33]:
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = sklearn.model_selection.train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.25)

However, we don't know what type of model will predict our data best, so we need to test a couple that seem good. To do this we use 10-fold cross-validation to compare a Random Forest, KNN, and Logistic Regression model. The cross-validation compares how well the different classifiers perform while being trained and tested on different subsets of the training data.
We also use the warnings module here to capture deprecation warnings, which cross_val_score emits due to its use of older numpy functions.

In [34]:
n_train = X_train.shape[0]
n_folds = 10

rf_clf = sklearn.ensemble.RandomForestClassifier()
knn_clf = sklearn.neighbors.KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors=np.sqrt(n_train))
lgr_clf = sklearn.linear_model.LogisticRegression()

# ignore deprecation error
with warnings.catch_warnings():
    warnings.simplefilter('ignore')
    
    rf_scores = sklearn.model_selection.cross_val_score(rf_clf, X_train, y_train, cv=n_folds)
    knn_scores = sklearn.model_selection.cross_val_score(knn_clf, X_train, y_train, cv=n_folds)
    lgr_scores = sklearn.model_selection.cross_val_score(lgr_clf, X_train, y_train, cv=n_folds)

Having computed the cross validation scores, we can now compare them to determine the best model. We use a t-test to compare their scores.

In [35]:
t_val, p_val = scipy.stats.ttest_ind(rf_scores, knn_scores)
print('Probability Random Forest and KNN have similar mean accuracy:')
print('\tt = {}\n\tp = {}'.format(t_val, p_val))
print('Probability Random Forest is superior:')
print('\tp = {}'.format(p_val/2))

Probability Random Forest and KNN have similar mean accuracy:
	t = -6.225452856028759
	p = 7.125779029677536e-06
Probability Random Forest is superior:
	p = 3.562889514838768e-06

Based on this, we can conclude that a KNN will better model the data than a Random Forest classifier.

In [36]:
t_val, p_val = scipy.stats.ttest_ind(knn_scores, lgr_scores)
print('Probability KNN and Logistic Regression have similar mean accuracy:')
print('\tt = {}\n\tp = {}'.format(t_val, p_val))
print('Probability KNN is superior:')
print('\tp = {}'.format(p_val/2))

Probability KNN and Logistic Regression have similar mean accuracy:
	t = -4.2500702190509525
	p = 0.0004815877129892701

	p = 0.00024079385649463506

Based on these results, we can conclude that a Logistic Regression Classifier is more accurate than both the KNN and Random Forest classifiers.

In [37]:
model = sklearn.linear_model.LogisticRegression()
model.fit(X_train, y_train)
print(model.score(X_test, y_test))

0.827860126116

We can see from this that our final accuracy on the testing data is about 82%.

Conclusions¶

We found in our Exploratory Data Analysis that all variables -- age, gender, race, etc. -- can have a significant impact on expected salary being greater than or less than \$50K. All our plots and maps showed sharp differences between a few groups and the majority. Based on these charts, we hypothesized that race could be a significant factor in determining expected salary. To test this, we used a Student's t-test and found with = 0.01 that Asians had a higher percentage of members with salaries greater than $50K than the percentage of all the other races combined. Additionally, with = 0.01 Asians had a higher percentage of high salaries than each other race individually except for Whites.

The previous hypothesis testing showed that individual attributes of a person could significantly affect expected salary. Based on this, we decided to attempt to predict salary based on other factors given in the data. We split our data into 75% training data and 25% testing data for machine learning. We found that a Logistic Regression model best predicted the data compared to a K-Nearest-Neighbours and Random Forest classifier with = 0.01 significance. A Logistic Regression model trained on the data then scored 82.9% accuracy on testing data. For binary classification, this is much better than the expected 50% of random guessing, but is nowhere near perfect. From these results, it seems that while the variables given in the data can significantly affect expected salary, they do not divide up the space of people effectively enough for accurate classification.

For example, in deciding whether or not to give loans, banks must choose based on given information. Naturally some of the factors we include are considered protected variables in such decisions, but the model's accuracy is clearly far too low for a bank to actually use. From this we can conclude that the input variables we have do not have a significant enough effect on expected salary to accurately predict it.
